5. Public Inscriptions. It is needless to spealt of the multitude which must have been at the time in existence, or of their manifold value to historians. Tiberius is stated to have talten great pains early in his principate to preserve and restore ancient documents ⁸. We have, how· ever, no evidence that Tacitus was in the habit of consulting inscriptions, though he makes mention of decrees so recorded⁴, and once refers to such evidence of the letters added to the alphabet by Claudius ⁸.
